{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782386922390,"sessionID":"ses_1017781abffe8Jf4LLgGRFccm9","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"call_b222ef3269c54ff7bf471a88","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/001-corpus-research/research/lineages/mimo25pro/deep-research-config.json","content":"{\n  \"topic\": \"Determine how to restructure the existing sk-design-interface skill into a parent skill named sk-design that contains multiple focused design sub-skills, grounded in the external design-skills corpus at .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external (41 standalone design-skill docs, the designer-skills-main 9-collection/97-skill model, and apple-bento-grid-main). Produce three things: (1) the optimal sub-skill taxonomy of 4 to 7 children, each with its scope, boundaries, and the specific corpus sources that feed it; (2) evidence for the parent structural model, comparing a single hub with nested mode packets against an umbrella router over a sibling family, including coupling and shared-runtime signals; (3) per-child onboarding and backward-compatibility implications, including how to fold in the existing sk-design-interface and sk-design-md-generator skills.\",\n  \"maxIterations\": 8,\n  \"convergenceThreshold\": 0.05,\n  \"stuckThreshold\": 3,\n  \"maxDurationMinutes\": 120,\n  \"maxToolCallsPerIteration\": 12,\n  \"maxMinutesPerIteration\": 15,\n  \"progressiveSynthesis\": true,\n  \"specFolder\": \".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/001-corpus-research\",\n  \"createdAt\": \"2026-06-25T12:00:00Z\",\n  \"status\": \"initialized\",\n  \"executionMode\": \"auto\",\n  \"executor\": {\n    \"kind\": \"cli-opencode\",\n    \"model\": \"xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro\",\n    \"reasoningEffort\": \"high\",\n    \"serviceTier\": null,\n    \"sandboxMode\": null,\n    \"timeoutSeconds\": 1200\n  },\n  \"lineage\": {\n    \"sessionId\": \"fanout-mimo25pro-1782386817945-6shco2\",\n    \"parentSessionId\": null,\n    \"lineageMode\": \"new\",\n    \"allowedModes\": [\"new\", \"resume\", \"restart\"],\n    \"deferredModes\": [\"fork\", \"completed-continue\"],\n    \"generation\": 1,\n    \"continuedFromRun\": null\n  },\n  \"reducer\": {\n    \"enabled\": true,\n    \"version\": \"1.0\",\n    \"registryFile\": \"research/lineages/mimo25pro/findings-registry.json\",\n    \"dashboardFile\": \"research/lineages/mimo25pro/deep-research-dashboard.md\",\n    \"strategyFile\": \"research/lineages/mimo25pro/deep-research-strategy.md\",\n    \"machineOwnedSections\": [\n      \"key-questions\",\n      \"answered-questions\",\n      \"what-worked\",\n      \"what-failed\",\n      \"exhausted-approaches\",\n      \"ruled-out-directions\",\n      \"next-focus\"\n    ]\n  },\n  \"fileProtection\": {\n    \"deep-research-config.json\": \"immutable\",\n    \"deep-research-state.jsonl\": \"append-only\",\n    \"deep-research-strategy.md\": \"mutable\",\n    \"deep-research-dashboard.md\": \"auto-generated\",\n    \"findings-registry.json\": \"auto-generated\",\n    \"iteration-*.md\": \"write-once\",\n    \"research.md\": \"mutable\"\n  }\n}\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/001-corpus-research/research/lineages/mimo25pro/deep-research-config.json","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/001-corpus-research/research/lineages/mimo25pro/deep-research-config.json","time":{"start":1782386922382,"end":1782386922389}},"id":"prt_efe8a138800167m6qlyCPP0aXi","sessionID":"ses_1017781abffe8Jf4LLgGRFccm9","messageID":"msg_efe89e6960011ZBf4rbvlPmsD9"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1782386939190,"sessionID":"ses_1017781abffe8Jf4LLgGRFccm9","part":{"id":"prt_efe89f284001DXb34Qnzhd7QUv","messageID":"msg_efe89e6960011ZBf4rbvlPmsD9","sessionID":"ses_1017781abffe8Jf4LLgGRFccm9","type":"text","text":"Now I'll create the deep-research state files for the mimo25pro lineage.","time":{"start":1782386913924,"end":1782386939188}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782386939195,"sessionID":"ses_1017781abffe8Jf4LLgGRFccm9","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"call_40467ca1285f46099c1ee116","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/001-corpus-research/research/lineages/mimo25pro/deep-research-strategy.md","content":"---\ntitle: Deep Research Strategy - mimo25pro lineage\ndescription: Research strategy for the sk-design parent skill restructuring analysis\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"sk-design restructuring research\"\n  - \"design skill taxonomy\"\n  - \"design parent skill architecture\"\nimportance_tier: important\ncontextType: planning\nversion: 1.0.0\n---\n\n# Deep Research Strategy - mimo25pro Lineage\n\n## 2. TOPIC\n\nDetermine how to restructure the existing sk-design-interface skill into a parent skill named sk-design that contains multiple focused design sub-skills, grounded in the external design-skills corpus (41 standalone design-skill docs, the designer-skills-main 9-collection/97-skill model, and apple-bento-grid-main).\n\n---\n\n## 3. KEY QUESTIONS (remaining)\n\n- [ ] What is the optimal sub-skill taxonomy of 4-7 children for sk-design, each with scope, boundaries, and specific corpus sources?\n- [ ] What structural model is best: single hub with nested mode packets vs. umbrella router over a sibling family?\n- [ ] What coupling and shared-runtime signals exist between the candidate sub-skills?\n- [ ] How should the existing sk-design-interface and sk-design-md-generator skills be folded into the family?\n- [ ] What are the per-child onboarding and backward-compatibility implications?\n- [ ] How does the designer-skills-main 9-collection model map to the opencode skill architecture?\n- [ ] What shared resources (references, assets, scripts) should live at the parent level vs. in sub-skills?\n\n---\n\n## 4. NON-GOALS\n\n- This research does NOT make the final architecture decision (owned by 002-architecture-decision)\n- This research does NOT scaffold or build any skills (owned by phases 003-005)\n- This research does NOT evaluate transport integrations (mcp-figma, mcp-open-design remain separate)\n- This research does NOT author the design-judgment content inside each sub-skill\n\n---\n\n## 5. STOP CONDITIONS\n\n- All 8 iterations completed (maxIterations reached)\n- OR: composite convergence score > 0.60 with quality guards passing\n- OR: all key questions answered with evidence from corpus\n\n---\n\n## 6. ANSWERED QUESTIONS\n\n[None yet -- populated as iterations answer questions]\n\n---\n\n## 7. WHAT WORKED\n\n[First iteration -- populated after iteration 1 completes]\n\n---\n\n## 8. WHAT FAILED\n\n[First iteration -- populated after iteration 1 completes]\n\n---\n\n## 9. EXHAUSTED APPROACHES (do not retry)\n\n[Populated when an approach has been tried from multiple angles without success]\n\n---\n\n## 10. RULED OUT DIRECTIONS\n\n[Approaches that were investigated and definitively eliminated]\n\n---\n\n## 11A. CARRIED-FORWARD OPEN QUESTIONS\n\n[Self-owned open questions from iteration write-back]\n\n---\n\n## 11. NEXT FOCUS\n\nInitial scan of the full external corpus to categorize all 43 documents by design domain and identify natural clustering patterns that could inform sub-skill boundaries.\n\n---\n\n## 12. KNOWN CONTEXT\n\n### External Corpus Inventory (43 items)\n\n**41 Standalone Design-Skill Docs:**\n- UI/Visual: taste-skill.md, colorize.md, layout.md, oklch-skill.md, bolder.md, quieter.md, soft-skill.md, polish.md, impeccable.md, delight.md, overdrive.md\n- Motion/Animation: 12-principles-of-animation.md, animate.md, mastering-animate-presence.md, morphing-icons.md, fixing-motion-performance.md\n- Accessibility: fixing-accessibility.md\n- Interaction: interaction-design.md, pseudo-elements.md\n- Process/Audit: audit.md, baseline.md, critique.md, clarify.md, distill.md, fix, harden.md, optimize.md, redesign-skill.md, output-skill.md\n- Design Systems: canvas-design.md, design-lab.md, stitch-skill.md\n- Meta/Router: ui-skills-root.md, adapt.md\n- Style references: minimalist-skill.md, brutalist-skill.md, emil-design-eng.md, bencium-innovative-ux-designer.md, gpt-tasteskill.md, make-interfaces-feel-better.md\n- Content: frontend-slides.md, slidev.md\n\n**designer-skills-main (9-collection/97-skill model):**\n- 9 plugins: design-research (12 skills), design-systems (11), ux-strategy (12), ui-design (14), interaction-design (16), prototyping-testing (8), design-ops (9), designer-toolkit (7), visual-critique (7)\n- 30 commands across 9 plugins\n\n**apple-bento-grid-main:**\n- Bento grid design system, layout patterns, evaluation framework\n\n### Existing Skills to Fold In\n- `sk-design-interface`: Visual identity, palette, typography, layout, anti-default critique (Anthropic-sourced, Apache-2.0)\n- `sk-design-md-generator`: CSS extraction pipeline, DESIGN.md v3 Style Reference format, Playwright crawler\n\n### Predecessor/Parent Context\n- Parent packet: `skilled-agent-orchestration`\n- Predecessor: `143-sk-design-interface` (matured the interface skill)\n- Phase-parent spec establishes sk-design as the family umbrella\n\n---\n\n## 13. RESEARCH BOUNDARIES\n\n- Max iterations: 8\n- Convergence threshold: 0.05\n- Per-iteration budget: 12 tool calls, 15 minutes\n- Progressive synthesis: true\n- research/research.md ownership: workflow-owned canonical synthesis output\n- Machine-owned sections: reducer controls Sections 3, 6, 7-11A\n- Current generation: 1\n- Started: 2026-06-25T12:00:00Z\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/001-corpus-research/research/lineages/mimo25pro/deep-research-strategy.md","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/001-corpus-research/research/lineages/mimo25pro/deep-research-strategy.md","time":{"start":1782386939186,"end":1782386939192}},"id":"prt_efe8a552e001kSE2eGe6i22EMM","sessionID":"ses_1017781abffe8Jf4LLgGRFccm9","messageID":"msg_efe89e6960011ZBf4rbvlPmsD9"}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1782386939709,"sessionID":"ses_1017781abffe8Jf4LLgGRFccm9","part":{"id":"prt_efe8a5739001xvg4i0NBXJFYLd","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"cef8a4d5cdb680824d9b1b571cc80539f59f33ef","messageID":"msg_efe89e6960011ZBf4rbvlPmsD9","sessionID":"ses_1017781abffe8Jf4LLgGRFccm9","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":108574,"input":3521,"output":2213,"reasoning":120,"cache":{"write":0,"read":102720}},"cost":0.031064}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1782386942150,"sessionID":"ses_1017781abffe8Jf4LLgGRFccm9","part":{"id":"prt_efe8a60c4001krpMFWAdjNU9Gm","messageID":"msg_efe8a5916001tUR9FUmiulTLwN","sessionID":"ses_1017781abffe8Jf4LLgGRFccm9","snapshot":"cef8a4d5cdb680824d9b1b571cc80539f59f33ef","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782386945224,"sessionID":"ses_1017781abffe8Jf4LLgGRFccm9","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_152b7c9c3dd34a6c9c462247","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/animate.md","limit":30},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/animate.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: name: animate\n3: description: \"Enhance UX with purposeful animation and micro-interactions that support usability and delight.\"\n4: ---\n5: \n6: # Animate\n7: \n8: > **Additional context needed**: performance constraints.\n9: \n10: Add motion that conveys state, gives feedback, and clarifies hierarchy. Cut motion that exists only for decoration. Animation fatigue is a real cost; spend the budget on the moments that need it.\n11: \n12: ---\n13: \n14: ## Register\n15: \n16: Brand: motion is part of the voice; one well-rehearsed entrance beats scattered micro-interactions. The saturated AI default is fade-and-rise reveals on every scrolled section; that's a tell, not a choreography. Reserve scroll-triggered motion for moments that earn it.\n17: \n18: Product: 150–250 ms on most transitions. Motion conveys state: feedback, reveal, loading, transitions between views. No page-load choreography; users are in a task and won't wait for it.\n19: \n20: ---\n21: \n22: ## Assess Animation Opportunities\n23: \n24: Analyze where motion would improve the experience:\n25: \n26: 1. **Identify static areas**:\n27:    - **Missing feedback**: Actions without visual acknowledgment (button clicks, form submission, etc.)\n28:    - **Jarring transitions**: Instant state changes that feel abrupt (show/hide, page loads, route changes)\n29:    - **Unclear relationships**: Spatial or hierarchical relationships that aren't obvious\n30:    - **Lack of delight**: Functional but joyless interactions\n\n(Showing lines 1-30 of 208. Use offset=31 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nname: animate\ndescription: \"Enhance UX with purposeful animation and micro-interactions that support usability and delight.\"\n---\n\n# Animate\n\n> **Additional context needed**: performance constraints.\n\nAdd motion that conveys state, gives feedback, and clarifies hierarchy. Cut motion that exists only for decoration. Animation fatigue is a real cost; spend the budget on the moments that need it.\n\n---\n\n## Register\n\nBrand: motion is part of the voice; one well-rehearsed entrance beats scattered micro-interactions. The saturated AI default is fade-and-rise reveals on every scrolled section; that's a tell, not a choreography. Reserve scroll-triggered motion for moments that earn it.\n\nProduct: 150–250 ms on most transitions. Motion conveys state: feedback, reveal, loading, transitions between views. No page-load choreography; users are in a task and won't wait for it.\n\n---","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/animate.md","text":"---\nname: animate\ndescription: \"Enhance UX with purposeful animation and micro-interactions that support usability and delight.\"\n---\n\n# Animate\n\n> **Additional context needed**: performance constraints.\n\nAdd motion that conveys state, gives feedback, and clarifies hierarchy. Cut motion that exists only for decoration. Animation fatigue is a real cost; spend the budget on the moments that need it.\n\n---\n\n## Register\n\nBrand: motion is part of the voice; one well-rehearsed entrance beats scattered micro-interactions. The saturated AI default is fade-and-rise reveals on every scrolled section; that's a tell, not a choreography. Reserve scroll-triggered motion for moments that earn it.\n\nProduct: 150–250 ms on most transitions. Motion conveys state: feedback, reveal, loading, transitions between views. No page-load choreography; users are in a task and won't wait for it.\n\n---\n\n## Assess Animation Opportunities\n\nAnalyze where motion would improve the experience:\n\n1. **Identify static areas**:\n   - **Missing feedback**: Actions without visual acknowledgment (button clicks, form submission, etc.)\n   - **Jarring transitions**: Instant state changes that feel abrupt (show/hide, page loads, route changes)\n   - **Unclear relationships**: Spatial or hierarchical relationships that aren't obvious\n   - **Lack of delight**: Functional but joyless interactions","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":30,"totalLines":208,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/animate.md","time":{"start":1782386945217,"end":1782386945223}},"id":"prt_efe8a6cbe001YmQQuDk05kBahs","sessionID":"ses_1017781abffe8Jf4LLgGRFccm9","messageID":"msg_efe8a5916001tUR9FUmiulTLwN"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782386945911,"sessionID":"ses_1017781abffe8Jf4LLgGRFccm9","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_5a2ad959f47d4518ad4ec99b","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/layout.md","limit":30},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/layout.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: name: layout\n3: description: \"Fix spacing, rhythm, grouping, alignment, and visual hierarchy across interface layouts.\"\n4: ---\n5: \n6: # Layout\n7: \n8: Space is the most underused design tool. Find the layout's actual problem (monotone spacing, weak hierarchy, identical card grids) and fix the structure, not the surface.\n9: \n10: ---\n11: \n12: ## Register\n13: \n14: Brand: asymmetric compositions, fluid spacing with `clamp()`, intentional grid-breaking for emphasis. Rhythm through contrast: tight groupings paired with generous separations.\n15: \n16: Product: predictable grids, consistent densities, familiar navigation patterns. Responsive behavior is structural (collapse sidebar, responsive table), not fluid typography. Consistency IS an affordance.\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## Assess Current Layout\n21: \n22: Analyze what's weak about the current spatial design:\n23: \n24: 1. **Spacing**:\n25:    - Is spacing consistent or arbitrary? (Random padding/margin values)\n26:    - Is all spacing the same? (Equal padding everywhere = no rhythm)\n27:    - Are related elements grouped tightly, with generous space between groups?\n28: \n29: 2. **Visual hierarchy**:\n30:    - Apply the squint test: blur your (metaphorical) eyes. Can you still identify the most important element, second most important, and clear groupings?\n\n(Showing lines 1-30 of 168. Use offset=31 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nname: layout\ndescription: \"Fix spacing, rhythm, grouping, alignment, and visual hierarchy across interface layouts.\"\n---\n\n# Layout\n\nSpace is the most underused design tool. Find the layout's actual problem (monotone spacing, weak hierarchy, identical card grids) and fix the structure, not the surface.\n\n---\n\n## Register\n\nBrand: asymmetric compositions, fluid spacing with `clamp()`, intentional grid-breaking for emphasis. Rhythm through contrast: tight groupings paired with generous separations.\n\nProduct: predictable grids, consistent densities, familiar navigation patterns. Responsive behavior is structural (collapse sidebar, responsive table), not fluid typography. Consistency IS an affordance.\n\n---\n\n## Assess Current Layout","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/layout.md","text":"---\nname: layout\ndescription: \"Fix spacing, rhythm, grouping, alignment, and visual hierarchy across interface layouts.\"\n---\n\n# Layout\n\nSpace is the most underused design tool. Find the layout's actual problem (monotone spacing, weak hierarchy, identical card grids) and fix the structure, not the surface.\n\n---\n\n## Register\n\nBrand: asymmetric compositions, fluid spacing with `clamp()`, intentional grid-breaking for emphasis. Rhythm through contrast: tight groupings paired with generous separations.\n\nProduct: predictable grids, consistent densities, familiar navigation patterns. Responsive behavior is structural (collapse sidebar, responsive table), not fluid typography. Consistency IS an affordance.\n\n---\n\n## Assess Current Layout\n\nAnalyze what's weak about the current spatial design:\n\n1. **Spacing**:\n   - Is spacing consistent or arbitrary? (Random padding/margin values)\n   - Is all spacing the same? (Equal padding everywhere = no rhythm)\n   - Are related elements grouped tightly, with generous space between groups?\n\n2. **Visual hierarchy**:\n   - Apply the squint test: blur your (metaphorical) eyes. Can you still identify the most important element, second most important, and clear groupings?","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":30,"totalLines":168,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/layout.md","time":{"start":1782386945906,"end":1782386945910}},"id":"prt_efe8a6f6f001Vzkgc81EYKL9DZ","sessionID":"ses_1017781abffe8Jf4LLgGRFccm9","messageID":"msg_efe8a5916001tUR9FUmiulTLwN"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782386946660,"sessionID":"ses_1017781abffe8Jf4LLgGRFccm9","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_40763f1269b84e5c8c1ef05c","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/audit.md","limit":30},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/audit.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: name: audit\n3: description: \"Run technical UI quality audits across accessibility, performance, theming, responsive behavior, and anti-patterns.\"\n4: ---\n5: \n6: # Audit\n7: \n8: Run systematic **technical** quality checks and generate a comprehensive report. Don't fix issues; document them for other commands to address.\n9: \n10: This is a code-level audit, not a design critique. Check what's measurable and verifiable in the implementation.\n11: \n12: ## Diagnostic Scan\n13: \n14: Run comprehensive checks across 5 dimensions. Score each dimension 0-4 using the criteria below.\n15: \n16: ### 1. Accessibility (A11y)\n17: \n18: **Check for**:\n19: - **Contrast issues**: Text contrast ratios < 4.5:1 (or 7:1 for AAA)\n20: - **Missing ARIA**: Interactive elements without proper roles, labels, or states\n21: - **Keyboard navigation**: Missing focus indicators, illogical tab order, keyboard traps\n22: - **Semantic HTML**: Improper heading hierarchy, missing landmarks, divs instead of buttons\n23: - **Alt text**: Missing or poor image descriptions\n24: - **Form issues**: Inputs without labels, poor error messaging, missing required indicators\n25: \n26: **Score 0-4**: 0=Inaccessible (fails WCAG A), 1=Major gaps (few ARIA labels, no keyboard nav), 2=Partial (some a11y effort, significant gaps), 3=Good (WCAG AA mostly met, minor gaps), 4=Excellent (WCAG AA fully met, approaches AAA)\n27: \n28: ### 2. Performance\n29: \n30: **Check for**:\n\n(Showing lines 1-30 of 139. Use offset=31 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nname: audit\ndescription: \"Run technical UI quality audits across accessibility, performance, theming, responsive behavior, and anti-patterns.\"\n---\n\n# Audit\n\nRun systematic **technical** quality checks and generate a comprehensive report. Don't fix issues; document them for other commands to address.\n\nThis is a code-level audit, not a design critique. Check what's measurable and verifiable in the implementation.\n\n## Diagnostic Scan\n\nRun comprehensive checks across 5 dimensions. Score each dimension 0-4 using the criteria below.\n\n### 1. Accessibility (A11y)\n\n**Check for**:\n- **Contrast issues**: Text contrast ratios < 4.5:1 (or 7:1 for AAA)\n- **Missing ARIA**: Interactive elements without proper roles, labels, or states","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/audit.md","text":"---\nname: audit\ndescription: \"Run technical UI quality audits across accessibility, performance, theming, responsive behavior, and anti-patterns.\"\n---\n\n# Audit\n\nRun systematic **technical** quality checks and generate a comprehensive report. Don't fix issues; document them for other commands to address.\n\nThis is a code-level audit, not a design critique. Check what's measurable and verifiable in the implementation.\n\n## Diagnostic Scan\n\nRun comprehensive checks across 5 dimensions. Score each dimension 0-4 using the criteria below.\n\n### 1. Accessibility (A11y)\n\n**Check for**:\n- **Contrast issues**: Text contrast ratios < 4.5:1 (or 7:1 for AAA)\n- **Missing ARIA**: Interactive elements without proper roles, labels, or states\n- **Keyboard navigation**: Missing focus indicators, illogical tab order, keyboard traps\n- **Semantic HTML**: Improper heading hierarchy, missing landmarks, divs instead of buttons\n- **Alt text**: Missing or poor image descriptions\n- **Form issues**: Inputs without labels, poor error messaging, missing required indicators\n\n**Score 0-4**: 0=Inaccessible (fails WCAG A), 1=Major gaps (few ARIA labels, no keyboard nav), 2=Partial (some a11y effort, significant gaps), 3=Good (WCAG AA mostly met, minor gaps), 4=Excellent (WCAG AA fully met, approaches AAA)\n\n### 2. Performance\n\n**Check for**:","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":30,"totalLines":139,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/audit.md","time":{"start":1782386946653,"end":1782386946659}},"id":"prt_efe8a725a001yVS8sIVLnnDVJN","sessionID":"ses_1017781abffe8Jf4LLgGRFccm9","messageID":"msg_efe8a5916001tUR9FUmiulTLwN"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1782386947438,"sessionID":"ses_1017781abffe8Jf4LLgGRFccm9","part":{"id":"prt_efe8a667d001RGUvOsemo6jwFU","messageID":"msg_efe8a5916001tUR9FUmiulTLwN","sessionID":"ses_1017781abffe8Jf4LLgGRFccm9","type":"text","text":"**Phase Init complete.** Config, strategy, and directory structure created. Now beginning the 8-iteration research loop.\n\n---\n\n## ITERATION 1: Corpus Categorization\n\nFocus: Scan the full external corpus and categorize all 43 documents by design domain to identify natural clustering patterns.","time":{"start":1782386943613,"end":1782386947436}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782386947461,"sessionID":"ses_1017781abffe8Jf4LLgGRFccm9","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_cf55e02009d94311ac123deb","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/critique.md","limit":30},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/critique.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: name: critique\n3: description: \"Evaluate design quality with structured UX scoring, persona checks, and actionable remediation guidance.\"\n4: ---\n5: \n6: # Critique\n7: \n8: ### Purpose\n9: \n10: Resolve one stable target, run two independent assessments, synthesize a design critique, persist a snapshot, and ask the user what to improve next. The chat response is the primary deliverable; the snapshot is an archive/backlog for future commands.\n11: \n12: ### Hard Invariants\n13: \n14: - Assessment A (design review) and Assessment B (detector/browser evidence) are both required.\n15: - Assessment A must finish before detector findings enter the parent synthesis context. Detector output is deterministic, but it still anchors judgment.\n16: - If sub-agents are unavailable, fall back sequentially: finish and record Assessment A first, then run Assessment B, then synthesize.\n17: - A skipped detector is a failed critique run unless `detect.mjs` is missing or crashes after a real attempt.\n18: - Viewable targets require browser inspection when available.\n19: - Any local server started only for critique visualization must run in the background, have a recorded stop method, and be stopped before final reporting unless the user asks to keep it.\n20: - Do not claim a user-visible overlay exists unless script injection succeeded and the detector ran in the page.\n21: \n22: ### Setup\n23: \n24: 1. **Resolve the target** to a concrete file path or URL. Prefer a source path over a dev-server URL when both identify the same surface; ports drift, paths do not.\n25:    - \"the homepage\" -> `site/pages/index.astro` or `index.html`\n26:    - \"the settings modal\" -> the primary component file\n27:    - \"this page\" -> the current URL or source file\n28: 2. **Compute the slug**:\n29:    ```bash\n30:    node {{scripts_path}}/critique-storage.mjs slug \"<resolved-path-or-url>\"\n\n(Showing lines 1-30 of 812. Use offset=31 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nname: critique\ndescription: \"Evaluate design quality with structured UX scoring, persona checks, and actionable remediation guidance.\"\n---\n\n# Critique\n\n### Purpose\n\nResolve one stable target, run two independent assessments, synthesize a design critique, persist a snapshot, and ask the user what to improve next. The chat response is the primary deliverable; the snapshot is an archive/backlog for future commands.\n\n### Hard Invariants\n\n- Assessment A (design review) and Assessment B (detector/browser evidence) are both required.\n- Assessment A must finish before detector findings enter the parent synthesis context. Detector output is deterministic, but it still anchors judgment.\n- If sub-agents are unavailable, fall back sequentially: finish and record Assessment A first, then run Assessment B, then synthesize.\n- A skipped detector is a failed critique run unless `detect.mjs` is missing or crashes after a real attempt.\n- Viewable targets require browser inspection when available.\n- Any local server started only for critique visualization must run in the background, have a recorded stop method, and be stopped before final reporting unless the user asks to keep it.\n- Do not claim a user-visible overlay exists unless script injection succeeded and the detector ran in the page.","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/critique.md","text":"---\nname: critique\ndescription: \"Evaluate design quality with structured UX scoring, persona checks, and actionable remediation guidance.\"\n---\n\n# Critique\n\n### Purpose\n\nResolve one stable target, run two independent assessments, synthesize a design critique, persist a snapshot, and ask the user what to improve next. The chat response is the primary deliverable; the snapshot is an archive/backlog for future commands.\n\n### Hard Invariants\n\n- Assessment A (design review) and Assessment B (detector/browser evidence) are both required.\n- Assessment A must finish before detector findings enter the parent synthesis context. Detector output is deterministic, but it still anchors judgment.\n- If sub-agents are unavailable, fall back sequentially: finish and record Assessment A first, then run Assessment B, then synthesize.\n- A skipped detector is a failed critique run unless `detect.mjs` is missing or crashes after a real attempt.\n- Viewable targets require browser inspection when available.\n- Any local server started only for critique visualization must run in the background, have a recorded stop method, and be stopped before final reporting unless the user asks to keep it.\n- Do not claim a user-visible overlay exists unless script injection succeeded and the detector ran in the page.\n\n### Setup\n\n1. **Resolve the target** to a concrete file path or URL. Prefer a source path over a dev-server URL when both identify the same surface; ports drift, paths do not.\n   - \"the homepage\" -> `site/pages/index.astro` or `index.html`\n   - \"the settings modal\" -> the primary component file\n   - \"this page\" -> the current URL or source file\n2. **Compute the slug**:\n   ```bash\n   node {{scripts_path}}/critique-storage.mjs slug \"<resolved-path-or-url>\"","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":30,"totalLines":812,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/critique.md","time":{"start":1782386947433,"end":1782386947459}},"id":"prt_efe8a7567001lZYUA9g7YKI3aU","sessionID":"ses_1017781abffe8Jf4LLgGRFccm9","messageID":"msg_efe8a5916001tUR9FUmiulTLwN"}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1782386947977,"sessionID":"ses_1017781abffe8Jf4LLgGRFccm9","part":{"id":"prt_efe8a7786001jJBqnrl1EYuINw","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"cef8a4d5cdb680824d9b1b571cc80539f59f33ef","messageID":"msg_efe8a5916001tUR9FUmiulTLwN","sessionID":"ses_1017781abffe8Jf4LLgGRFccm9","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":109006,"input":2423,"output":343,"reasoning":64,"cache":{"write":0,"read":106176}},"cost":0.0248792}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1782386952855,"sessionID":"ses_1017781abffe8Jf4LLgGRFccm9","part":{"id":"prt_efe8a8a95001k1p36cJN5I0ANZ","messageID":"msg_efe8a7a31001s3wGmiptWKODR6","sessionID":"ses_1017781abffe8Jf4LLgGRFccm9","snapshot":"cef8a4d5cdb680824d9b1b571cc80539f59f33ef","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782386953932,"sessionID":"ses_1017781abffe8Jf4LLgGRFccm9","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_88a994c5b2754c12829ca1a6","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/polish.md","limit":30},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/polish.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: name: polish\n3: description: \"Run a final quality pass before shipping, tightening visual detail, accessibility, responsiveness, and interaction polish.\"\n4: ---\n5: \n6: # Polish\n7: \n8: > **Additional context needed**: quality bar (MVP vs flagship).\n9: \n10: Perform a meticulous final pass to catch all the small details that separate good work from great work. The difference between shipped and polished.\n11: \n12: Detector and automated QA output are defect evidence only. A clean script result is never proof that the design is strong; gather browser evidence and inspect the real interaction path.\n13: \n14: ## Design System Discovery\n15: \n16: Aligning the feature to the design system is **not optional**. Polish without alignment is decoration on top of drift, and it makes the next person's job harder. Discovery comes before any other polish work.\n17: \n18: 1. **Find the design system**: Search for design system documentation, component libraries, style guides, or token definitions. Study the core patterns: design principles, target audience, color tokens, spacing scale, typography styles, component API, motion conventions.\n19: 2. **Note the conventions**: How are shared components imported? What spacing scale is used? Which colors come from tokens vs hard-coded values? What motion and interaction patterns are established? What flow shapes are used for comparable actions (modal vs full-page, inline vs route, save-on-blur vs explicit submit)?\n20: 3. **Identify drift, then name the root cause**: For every deviation, classify it as a **missing token** (the value should exist in the system but doesn't), a **one-off implementation** (a shared component already exists but wasn't used), or a **conceptual misalignment** (the feature's flow, IA, or hierarchy doesn't match neighboring features). The fix differs by category: patch the value, swap to the shared component, or rework the flow. Fixing the symptom without naming the cause is how drift compounds.\n21: \n22: If a design system exists, polish **must** align the feature with it. If none exists, polish against the conventions visible in the codebase. **If anything about the system is ambiguous, ask. Never guess at design system principles.**\n23: \n24: ## Pre-Polish Assessment\n25: \n26: Understand the current state and goals before touching anything:\n27: \n28: 1. **Review completeness**:\n29:    - Is it functionally complete?\n30:    - Are there known issues to preserve (mark with TODOs)?\n\n(Showing lines 1-30 of 248. Use offset=31 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nname: polish\ndescription: \"Run a final quality pass before shipping, tightening visual detail, accessibility, responsiveness, and interaction polish.\"\n---\n\n# Polish\n\n> **Additional context needed**: quality bar (MVP vs flagship).\n\nPerform a meticulous final pass to catch all the small details that separate good work from great work. The difference between shipped and polished.\n\nDetector and automated QA output are defect evidence only. A clean script result is never proof that the design is strong; gather browser evidence and inspect the real interaction path.\n\n## Design System Discovery\n\nAligning the feature to the design system is **not optional**. Polish without alignment is decoration on top of drift, and it makes the next person's job harder. Discovery comes before any other polish work.\n\n1. **Find the design system**: Search for design system documentation, component libraries, style guides, or token definitions. Study the core patterns: design principles, target audience, color tokens, spacing scale, typography styles, component API, motion conventions.\n2. **Note the conventions**: How are shared components imported? What spacing scale is used? Which colors come from tokens vs hard-coded values? What motion and interaction patterns are established? What flow shapes are used for comparable actions (modal vs full-page, inline vs route, save-on-blur vs explicit submit)?\n3. **Identify drift, then name the root cause**: For every deviation, classify it as a **missing token** (the value should exist in the system but doesn't), a **one-off implementation** (a shared component already exists but wasn't used), or a **conceptual misalignment** (the feature's flow, IA, or hierarchy doesn't match neighboring features). The fix differs by category: patch the value, swap to the shared component, or rework the flow. Fixing the symptom without naming the cause is how drift compounds.","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/polish.md","text":"---\nname: polish\ndescription: \"Run a final quality pass before shipping, tightening visual detail, accessibility, responsiveness, and interaction polish.\"\n---\n\n# Polish\n\n> **Additional context needed**: quality bar (MVP vs flagship).\n\nPerform a meticulous final pass to catch all the small details that separate good work from great work. The difference between shipped and polished.\n\nDetector and automated QA output are defect evidence only. A clean script result is never proof that the design is strong; gather browser evidence and inspect the real interaction path.\n\n## Design System Discovery\n\nAligning the feature to the design system is **not optional**. Polish without alignment is decoration on top of drift, and it makes the next person's job harder. Discovery comes before any other polish work.\n\n1. **Find the design system**: Search for design system documentation, component libraries, style guides, or token definitions. Study the core patterns: design principles, target audience, color tokens, spacing scale, typography styles, component API, motion conventions.\n2. **Note the conventions**: How are shared components imported? What spacing scale is used? Which colors come from tokens vs hard-coded values? What motion and interaction patterns are established? What flow shapes are used for comparable actions (modal vs full-page, inline vs route, save-on-blur vs explicit submit)?\n3. **Identify drift, then name the root cause**: For every deviation, classify it as a **missing token** (the value should exist in the system but doesn't), a **one-off implementation** (a shared component already exists but wasn't used), or a **conceptual misalignment** (the feature's flow, IA, or hierarchy doesn't match neighboring features). The fix differs by category: patch the value, swap to the shared component, or rework the flow. Fixing the symptom without naming the cause is how drift compounds.\n\nIf a design system exists, polish **must** align the feature with it. If none exists, polish against the conventions visible in the codebase. **If anything about the system is ambiguous, ask. Never guess at design system principles.**\n\n## Pre-Polish Assessment\n\nUnderstand the current state and goals before touching anything:\n\n1. **Review completeness**:\n   - Is it functionally complete?\n   - Are there known issues to preserve (mark with TODOs)?","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":30,"totalLines":248,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/polish.md","time":{"start":1782386953925,"end":1782386953930}},"id":"prt_efe8a8ec3001cVlI72EHysJfQM","sessionID":"ses_1017781abffe8Jf4LLgGRFccm9","messageID":"msg_efe8a7a31001s3wGmiptWKODR6"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782386954799,"sessionID":"ses_1017781abffe8Jf4LLgGRFccm9","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_f979b6eacaca4ed8be79820e","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/design-lab.md","limit":30},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/design-lab.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: name: design-lab\n3: description: Conduct design interviews, generate five distinct UI variations in a temporary design lab, collect feedback, and produce implementation plans. Use when the user wants to explore UI design options, redesign existing components, or create new UI with multiple approaches to compare.\n4: ---\n5: \n6: # Design Lab Skill\n7: \n8: This skill implements a complete design exploration workflow: interview, generate variations, collect feedback, refine, preview, and finalize.\n9: \n10: ## CRITICAL: Cleanup Behavior\n11: \n12: **All temporary files MUST be deleted when the process ends, whether by:**\n13: - User confirms final design → cleanup, then generate plan\n14: - User aborts/cancels → cleanup immediately, no plan generated\n15: \n16: **Never leave `.claude-design/` or `__design_lab` routes behind.** If the user says \"cancel\", \"abort\", \"stop\", or \"nevermind\" at any point, confirm and then delete all temporary artifacts.\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## Phase 0: Preflight Detection\n21: \n22: Before starting the interview, automatically detect:\n23: \n24: ### Package Manager\n25: Check for lock files in the project root:\n26: - `pnpm-lock.yaml` → use `pnpm`\n27: - `yarn.lock` → use `yarn`\n28: - `package-lock.json` → use `npm`\n29: - `bun.lockb` → use `bun`\n30: \n\n(Showing lines 1-30 of 920. Use offset=31 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nname: design-lab\ndescription: Conduct design interviews, generate five distinct UI variations in a temporary design lab, collect feedback, and produce implementation plans. Use when the user wants to explore UI design options, redesign existing components, or create new UI with multiple approaches to compare.\n---\n\n# Design Lab Skill\n\nThis skill implements a complete design exploration workflow: interview, generate variations, collect feedback, refine, preview, and finalize.\n\n## CRITICAL: Cleanup Behavior\n\n**All temporary files MUST be deleted when the process ends, whether by:**\n- User confirms final design → cleanup, then generate plan\n- User aborts/cancels → cleanup immediately, no plan generated\n\n**Never leave `.claude-design/` or `__design_lab` routes behind.** If the user says \"cancel\", \"abort\", \"stop\", or \"nevermind\" at any point, confirm and then delete all temporary artifacts.\n\n---\n\n## Phase 0: Preflight Detection","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/design-lab.md","text":"---\nname: design-lab\ndescription: Conduct design interviews, generate five distinct UI variations in a temporary design lab, collect feedback, and produce implementation plans. Use when the user wants to explore UI design options, redesign existing components, or create new UI with multiple approaches to compare.\n---\n\n# Design Lab Skill\n\nThis skill implements a complete design exploration workflow: interview, generate variations, collect feedback, refine, preview, and finalize.\n\n## CRITICAL: Cleanup Behavior\n\n**All temporary files MUST be deleted when the process ends, whether by:**\n- User confirms final design → cleanup, then generate plan\n- User aborts/cancels → cleanup immediately, no plan generated\n\n**Never leave `.claude-design/` or `__design_lab` routes behind.** If the user says \"cancel\", \"abort\", \"stop\", or \"nevermind\" at any point, confirm and then delete all temporary artifacts.\n\n---\n\n## Phase 0: Preflight Detection\n\nBefore starting the interview, automatically detect:\n\n### Package Manager\nCheck for lock files in the project root:\n- `pnpm-lock.yaml` → use `pnpm`\n- `yarn.lock` → use `yarn`\n- `package-lock.json` → use `npm`\n- `bun.lockb` → use `bun`\n","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":30,"totalLines":920,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/design-lab.md","time":{"start":1782386954793,"end":1782386954798}},"id":"prt_efe8a92200015fPjJf2GJ3TUfv","sessionID":"ses_1017781abffe8Jf4LLgGRFccm9","messageID":"msg_efe8a7a31001s3wGmiptWKODR6"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782386955470,"sessionID":"ses_1017781abffe8Jf4LLgGRFccm9","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_80cb6c04102b46efb82c1c7b","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/oklch-skill.md","limit":30},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/oklch-skill.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: name: oklch-skill\n3: description: OKLCH color space for web projects. Convert hex/rgb/hsl to oklch, generate palettes, check contrast, handle gamut boundaries, and theme with Tailwind v4. Triggers on oklch, color conversion, palette generation, contrast ratio, gamut, display p3, design tokens, hue drift, chroma, dark mode colors.\n4: ---\n5: \n6: # OKLCH Colors\n7: \n8: OKLCH is a perceptually uniform color space where the numbers actually mean what you think they mean. Most color problems in CSS — broken palettes, failing contrast, hue drift — come from using color spaces that don't match how we see. OKLCH fixes the model so the tools work. To explore interactively, visit [oklch.fyi](https://oklch.fyi).\n9: \n10: ## Quick Reference\n11: \n12: | Category | When to use | Reference |\n13: | --- | --- | --- |\n14: | Conversion | Hex/rgb/hsl to oklch | [color-conversion.md](color-conversion.md) |\n15: | Palettes | Generate scales, multi-hue, dark mode | [palette-generation.md](palette-generation.md) |\n16: | Contrast | APCA/WCAG checks, fixing failing contrast | [accessibility-contrast.md](accessibility-contrast.md) |\n17: | Gamut & Tailwind | P3 fallbacks, `@theme` scales, gamut clamping | [gamut-and-tailwind.md](gamut-and-tailwind.md) |\n18: \n19: ## Why OKLCH\n20: \n21: - **Perceptual uniformity.** Equal L steps = equal brightness. `oklch(0.5 ...)` is visually mid. HSL's `lightness: 50%` varies wildly by hue.\n22: - **Stable hue.** HSL blue shifts toward purple as lightness changes. OKLCH hue stays constant across the full lightness range.\n23: - **Independent chroma.** Chroma is an absolute measure of colorfulness that doesn't depend on lightness. HSL saturation does.\n24: - **Finite gamut.** Not every oklch value maps to a displayable sRGB color. High-chroma values at certain hues will clip — gamut awareness is required.\n25: \n26: ## OKLCH Syntax\n27: \n28: ```\n29: oklch(L C H)\n30: oklch(L C H / alpha)\n\n(Showing lines 1-30 of 90. Use offset=31 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nname: oklch-skill\ndescription: OKLCH color space for web projects. Convert hex/rgb/hsl to oklch, generate palettes, check contrast, handle gamut boundaries, and theme with Tailwind v4. Triggers on oklch, color conversion, palette generation, contrast ratio, gamut, display p3, design tokens, hue drift, chroma, dark mode colors.\n---\n\n# OKLCH Colors\n\nOKLCH is a perceptually uniform color space where the numbers actually mean what you think they mean. Most color problems in CSS — broken palettes, failing contrast, hue drift — come from using color spaces that don't match how we see. OKLCH fixes the model so the tools work. To explore interactively, visit [oklch.fyi](https://oklch.fyi).\n\n## Quick Reference\n\n| Category | When to use | Reference |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Conversion | Hex/rgb/hsl to oklch | [color-conversion.md](color-conversion.md) |\n| Palettes | Generate scales, multi-hue, dark mode | [palette-generation.md](palette-generation.md) |\n| Contrast | APCA/WCAG checks, fixing failing contrast | [accessibility-contrast.md](accessibility-contrast.md) |\n| Gamut & Tailwind | P3 fallbacks, `@theme` scales, gamut clamping | [gamut-and-tailwind.md](gamut-and-tailwind.md) |\n\n## Why OKLCH\n","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/oklch-skill.md","text":"---\nname: oklch-skill\ndescription: OKLCH color space for web projects. Convert hex/rgb/hsl to oklch, generate palettes, check contrast, handle gamut boundaries, and theme with Tailwind v4. Triggers on oklch, color conversion, palette generation, contrast ratio, gamut, display p3, design tokens, hue drift, chroma, dark mode colors.\n---\n\n# OKLCH Colors\n\nOKLCH is a perceptually uniform color space where the numbers actually mean what you think they mean. Most color problems in CSS — broken palettes, failing contrast, hue drift — come from using color spaces that don't match how we see. OKLCH fixes the model so the tools work. To explore interactively, visit [oklch.fyi](https://oklch.fyi).\n\n## Quick Reference\n\n| Category | When to use | Reference |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Conversion | Hex/rgb/hsl to oklch | [color-conversion.md](color-conversion.md) |\n| Palettes | Generate scales, multi-hue, dark mode | [palette-generation.md](palette-generation.md) |\n| Contrast | APCA/WCAG checks, fixing failing contrast | [accessibility-contrast.md](accessibility-contrast.md) |\n| Gamut & Tailwind | P3 fallbacks, `@theme` scales, gamut clamping | [gamut-and-tailwind.md](gamut-and-tailwind.md) |\n\n## Why OKLCH\n\n- **Perceptual uniformity.** Equal L steps = equal brightness. `oklch(0.5 ...)` is visually mid. HSL's `lightness: 50%` varies wildly by hue.\n- **Stable hue.** HSL blue shifts toward purple as lightness changes. OKLCH hue stays constant across the full lightness range.\n- **Independent chroma.** Chroma is an absolute measure of colorfulness that doesn't depend on lightness. HSL saturation does.\n- **Finite gamut.** Not every oklch value maps to a displayable sRGB color. High-chroma values at certain hues will clip — gamut awareness is required.\n\n## OKLCH Syntax\n\n```\noklch(L C H)\noklch(L C H / alpha)","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":30,"totalLines":90,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/oklch-skill.md","time":{"start":1782386955465,"end":1782386955468}},"id":"prt_efe8a94c6001FZbpzfyhQm32vX","sessionID":"ses_1017781abffe8Jf4LLgGRFccm9","messageID":"msg_efe8a7a31001s3wGmiptWKODR6"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782386956024,"sessionID":"ses_1017781abffe8Jf4LLgGRFccm9","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_8eec779e4c044acbb0b88165","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/canvas-design.md","limit":30},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/canvas-design.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: name: canvas-design\n3: description: Create beautiful visual art in .png and .pdf documents using design philosophy. You should use this skill when the user asks to create a poster, piece of art, design, or other static piece. Create original visual designs, never copying existing artists' work to avoid copyright violations.\n4: license: Complete terms in LICENSE.txt\n5: ---\n6: \n7: These are instructions for creating design philosophies - aesthetic movements that are then EXPRESSED VISUALLY. Output only .md files, .pdf files, and .png files.\n8: \n9: Complete this in two steps:\n10: 1. Design Philosophy Creation (.md file)\n11: 2. Express by creating it on a canvas (.pdf file or .png file)\n12: \n13: First, undertake this task:\n14: \n15: ## DESIGN PHILOSOPHY CREATION\n16: \n17: To begin, create a VISUAL PHILOSOPHY (not layouts or templates) that will be interpreted through:\n18: - Form, space, color, composition\n19: - Images, graphics, shapes, patterns\n20: - Minimal text as visual accent\n21: \n22: ### THE CRITICAL UNDERSTANDING\n23: - What is received: Some subtle input or instructions by the user that should be taken into account, but used as a foundation; it should not constrain creative freedom.\n24: - What is created: A design philosophy/aesthetic movement.\n25: - What happens next: Then, the same version receives the philosophy and EXPRESSES IT VISUALLY - creating artifacts that are 90% visual design, 10% essential text.\n26: \n27: Consider this approach:\n28: - Write a manifesto for an art movement\n29: - The next phase involves making the artwork\n30: \n\n(Showing lines 1-30 of 130. Use offset=31 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nname: canvas-design\ndescription: Create beautiful visual art in .png and .pdf documents using design philosophy. You should use this skill when the user asks to create a poster, piece of art, design, or other static piece. Create original visual designs, never copying existing artists' work to avoid copyright violations.\nlicense: Complete terms in LICENSE.txt\n---\n\nThese are instructions for creating design philosophies - aesthetic movements that are then EXPRESSED VISUALLY. Output only .md files, .pdf files, and .png files.\n\nComplete this in two steps:\n1. Design Philosophy Creation (.md file)\n2. Express by creating it on a canvas (.pdf file or .png file)\n\nFirst, undertake this task:\n\n## DESIGN PHILOSOPHY CREATION\n\nTo begin, create a VISUAL PHILOSOPHY (not layouts or templates) that will be interpreted through:\n- Form, space, color, composition\n- Images, graphics, shapes, patterns\n- Minimal text as visual accent","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/canvas-design.md","text":"---\nname: canvas-design\ndescription: Create beautiful visual art in .png and .pdf documents using design philosophy. You should use this skill when the user asks to create a poster, piece of art, design, or other static piece. Create original visual designs, never copying existing artists' work to avoid copyright violations.\nlicense: Complete terms in LICENSE.txt\n---\n\nThese are instructions for creating design philosophies - aesthetic movements that are then EXPRESSED VISUALLY. Output only .md files, .pdf files, and .png files.\n\nComplete this in two steps:\n1. Design Philosophy Creation (.md file)\n2. Express by creating it on a canvas (.pdf file or .png file)\n\nFirst, undertake this task:\n\n## DESIGN PHILOSOPHY CREATION\n\nTo begin, create a VISUAL PHILOSOPHY (not layouts or templates) that will be interpreted through:\n- Form, space, color, composition\n- Images, graphics, shapes, patterns\n- Minimal text as visual accent\n\n### THE CRITICAL UNDERSTANDING\n- What is received: Some subtle input or instructions by the user that should be taken into account, but used as a foundation; it should not constrain creative freedom.\n- What is created: A design philosophy/aesthetic movement.\n- What happens next: Then, the same version receives the philosophy and EXPRESSES IT VISUALLY - creating artifacts that are 90% visual design, 10% essential text.\n\nConsider this approach:\n- Write a manifesto for an art movement\n- The next phase involves making the artwork\n","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":30,"totalLines":130,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/canvas-design.md","time":{"start":1782386956014,"end":1782386956022}},"id":"prt_efe8a96ea0019RXI5PICq6WHhN","sessionID":"ses_1017781abffe8Jf4LLgGRFccm9","messageID":"msg_efe8a7a31001s3wGmiptWKODR6"}}
